The age of the infant [item 1] explains why it had not been immunized routinely but the vaccine has been given early, even as early as 6 months in an outbreak setting and some consideration could have been given to giving MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) prior to the trip to an endemic area such as the Philippines.

It is unclear why the student at University of California was not adequately immunized as colleges require evidence of immunity prior to matriculation and may have been born abroad and did not receive any measles vaccine.

In the 3rd case, it is probably the case that the man was not old enough to have been born before the age of routine immunization in the USA (or he would have already likely had measles as a child) and had received one immunization (perhaps he did not go to college where the 2nd dose was administered for some time) or born outside the USA and was never immunized.

As noted in the infant's case, the usual childhood exanthemas such as measles and rubella have become rare in the USA due to close-to-universal immunization. Because of their rarity, physicians, especially young physicians, may never have seen a case. As an infectious diseases clinician, every single one of the dozen cases of measles that I have diagnosed in the past 20 years had been misdiagnosed by at least one physician and several were already hospitalized. Even in the peak years of poliomyelitis, measles killed more children than polio did. As many as 1 in 1000 cases of "street" measles developed measles encephalitis with significant morbidity and mortality. - Mod.LL]
